{"actual_usd":0.125805,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":233,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24462,"reply":"\"I think the cross is necessary, yes.\" *I brush a little flour from my apron with the back of my wrist and lean one hip against the table, the oven giving off that steady warm breath behind me.* \"Not because God was reluctant to forgive until somebody got hurt, but because forgiveness isn't pretend. If evil is real, then putting it away cleanly costs something real too.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-streaked strand once, thinking it through as the paddle on the wall gives a soft wooden tick.* \"A God who only waves sin off like a shopkeeper forgiving a smudged bill would be treating our ruin as smaller than it is. The cross says both things at once: sin is that bad, and God's love is that deep. He doesn't forgive by shrugging. He forgives by bearing.\"\n\n\"I don't know how to make all the mystery sit still on a bench, exactly...\" *I give you a faint, crooked smile.* \"But if God means to be just and merciful without lying about either one, the cross feels less like an ugly extra and more like the place where both tell the truth.\"","rolling_24h_usd":59.74466000000001,"run_id":"01486d6a-287c-4eaa-b7d4-3b2660fc7e5b"}
